<doc id="1035480" wikidata="Q3123021" url="?curid=1035480" title="Atlas languages">
<text>The Atlas languages are a subgroup of the Northern Berber languages of the Afro-Asiatic language family spoken in the Atlas Mountains of Morocco. By mutual intelligibility, they are a single language spoken by perhaps 14 million people; however, they are distinct sociolinguistically and are considered separate languages by the Royal institute of the Amazigh culture. They are:
* Central Atlas Tamazight (Central Atlas Berber), spoken in the central Atlas Mountains
* Shilha (&quot;Tashelhiyt&quot;; also rendered &quot;Tachelhit, Tasusit&quot;; includes Judeo-Berber and perhaps the extinct Lisan al-Gharbi), spoken in southern Morocco
* Sanhaja de Srair, spoken in the southern part of the Rif
* Ghomara, spoken in the western part of the Rif
* Lisan al-Gharbi, formerly spoken in western Morocco.

